1
00:00:00,858 --> 00:00:25,835
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassa

2
00:00:26,085 --> 00:00:30,955
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble, and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:32,137 --> 00:00:38,651
So this is the... We're celebrating the full moon of November, which is ahead of us, I think.

4
00:00:38,671 --> 00:00:40,314
It's the middle of next week.

5
00:00:41,036 --> 00:00:44,143
But it's convenient for us to come together on a Sunday.

6
00:00:44,182 --> 00:00:46,828
So...

7
00:00:47,128 --> 00:00:51,515
The topic for this month was livelihood, right livelihood.

8
00:00:52,137 --> 00:00:56,344
So I'll just go through the usual warnings that the Buddha gives.

9
00:00:56,945 --> 00:01:01,533
So the first is that we shouldn't engage in five types of business.

10
00:01:03,234 --> 00:01:05,058
So they're pretty straightforward, actually.

11
00:01:06,040 --> 00:01:09,204
The business of weapons, selling them, making them, etc.,

12
00:01:09,590 --> 00:01:13,515
Of course, it does question the role of the soldier.

13
00:01:13,575 --> 00:01:18,540
Remember, in the Buddha's time, it was really about conquest.

14
00:01:18,802 --> 00:01:27,153
The kings were trying to expand their kingdoms at the expense of tribal democracies.

15
00:01:28,073 --> 00:01:32,239
And the Buddha was definitely for the democracies, I think.

16
00:01:32,287 --> 00:01:37,871
He didn't like the way the kings were warring, often against each other.

17
00:01:37,912 --> 00:01:42,615
These days, of course, there's a call for a defence.

18
00:01:43,576 --> 00:01:45,537
So it's a slightly different era.

19
00:01:46,599 --> 00:01:56,326
So maybe we can't make these rules absolute, because it depends upon your take upon violence and all that.

20
00:01:56,346 --> 00:02:01,652
And as to whether there is such a thing as a justifiable armed intervention.

21
00:02:02,323 --> 00:02:06,030
But that's for somebody to write a book on.

22
00:02:08,652 --> 00:02:12,860
Then he says nobody should be involved in the business of people.

23
00:02:13,561 --> 00:02:19,028
So, of course, that's prostitution and modern-day slavery, which is absolutely awful.

24
00:02:21,552 --> 00:02:27,200
Indentured workers, workers that have fallen into debt and are working for a pittance.

25
00:02:30,639 --> 00:02:33,223
So we know that goes on anyway, you know.

26
00:02:34,204 --> 00:02:35,544
Then there's the whole business of meat.

27
00:02:37,287 --> 00:02:45,835
Now, monks are not supposed to eat any meat if they've seen, heard or suspected the animal has actually been killed for them specifically.

28
00:02:46,436 --> 00:02:49,098
So I've always thought the Buddha was a crypto vegan.

29
00:02:49,658 --> 00:02:57,947
But being a practical person, it wasn't as though he was going to make this hard and fast rule, which, of course, the Jains did.

30
00:02:57,926 --> 00:03:03,953
You know, you can't enter a Jain temple if you're wearing, say, a leather belt or leather shoes.

31
00:03:04,052 --> 00:03:04,993
They just won't let you in.

32
00:03:05,074 --> 00:03:08,617
They're absolutely, you know, the line is severe.

33
00:03:10,019 --> 00:03:14,082
But the Buddha never really did that, especially for lay people.

34
00:03:15,003 --> 00:03:17,926
They would always remember rules of training.

35
00:03:18,127 --> 00:03:19,489
It was never thou shalt.

36
00:03:19,868 --> 00:03:23,331
I undertake the rule of training not to kill, et cetera, et cetera.

37
00:03:25,334 --> 00:03:27,917
Then there's the business of intoxicants.

38
00:03:29,180 --> 00:03:37,189
So the West has this very refined, intoxicating industry of wine and beer.

39
00:03:38,671 --> 00:03:44,198
I don't think there's another culture that has quite the range of tastes.

40
00:03:44,799 --> 00:03:46,921
So it's a bit difficult for us to keep that one.

41
00:03:47,962 --> 00:03:52,048
But these days, more and more, you see these non-alcoholic things.

42
00:03:53,141 --> 00:04:03,556
I often wonder how a person feels who's taken this very seriously, working, shall we say, in Tesco's or a supermarket which sells alcohol.

43
00:04:04,236 --> 00:04:09,204
So I think you have to be careful that you don't take on other people's responsibilities.

44
00:04:13,569 --> 00:04:15,171
And then there's the business of poison.

45
00:04:15,331 --> 00:04:22,862
Well, we all know about Putin and his clever use of serine to get rid of enemies.

46
00:04:24,108 --> 00:04:26,853
But it was quite widespread, of course, in Renaissance Italy.

47
00:04:26,894 --> 00:04:30,762
The Borgias were especially good at it.

48
00:04:30,983 --> 00:04:37,177
And at the time, it said, nobody ever believed that popes, cardinals or royalty died natural deaths.

49
00:04:37,879 --> 00:04:38,961
It was that prevalent.

50
00:04:43,345 --> 00:04:47,509
So those are your five businesses that people shouldn't be engaged in.

51
00:04:47,911 --> 00:04:51,314
There is actually something for the monastics, too.

52
00:04:51,535 --> 00:05:03,730
It says that they shouldn't procure their requisites, whatever they need, through flattery, hinting, bribery, coercion or hypocrisy.

53
00:05:04,130 --> 00:05:09,538
So there's a whole load of mistakes that even in the monastic life you can make.

54
00:05:11,154 --> 00:05:19,326
So that just gives us just a grounding, really, of how the Buddha makes these limitations.

55
00:05:20,166 --> 00:05:28,718
But there's another particular discourse, the Upadatsutta, it's the discourse on the Holy Life.

56
00:05:28,737 --> 00:05:32,622
And Ananda, who's a very endearing character, says,

57
00:05:32,754 --> 00:05:38,165
You know, he he said to the Buddha that he would be his personal attendant.

58
00:05:38,185 --> 00:05:40,329
And he did so for the last 20 years of his life.

59
00:05:40,529 --> 00:05:42,694
So long as he heard everything the Buddha said.

60
00:05:43,115 --> 00:05:47,423
And if he wasn't there to hear it, the Buddha had to relate what he had said.

61
00:05:47,622 --> 00:05:51,468
And of course, Ananda then became this enormous audio memory.

62
00:05:52,170 --> 00:06:01,687
It's difficult for us to grasp that these days because we've become so visual and we've sold our memory to microchips.

63
00:06:03,870 --> 00:06:06,134
But he had this seemingly this phenomenal memory.

64
00:06:06,175 --> 00:06:10,963
And that's where the discourses come from, the Pali discourses.

65
00:06:12,276 --> 00:06:16,281
And he had the habit of thinking that he really had understood something.

66
00:06:16,302 --> 00:06:22,970
So there's a lovely moment where he says to the Buddha, you know, I think I've really got this dependence origination business.

67
00:06:23,410 --> 00:06:29,778
And the Buddha says, oh, no, the pen origination is deep, profound, etc.

68
00:06:29,877 --> 00:06:35,363
And he does the same with good companionship.

69
00:06:36,425 --> 00:06:41,271
So he says he thinks that good companionship is half of the holy life.

70
00:06:42,196 --> 00:06:46,641
having admirable good people as friends, companions and colleagues.

71
00:06:47,341 --> 00:06:50,444
And the Buddha says, oh, don't say that, Ananda.

72
00:06:51,345 --> 00:06:52,927
Don't say that.

73
00:06:52,947 --> 00:07:00,915
Having good admirable people as friends, companions and colleagues is actually the whole of the spiritual life.

74
00:07:00,935 --> 00:07:11,646
And when a monk or a monastic has admirable people as friends, companions and colleagues, they can be expected to develop and pursue the Noble Eightfold Path.

75
00:07:14,173 --> 00:07:40,303
So this definition of right livelihood as the spiritual life, our spiritual lives within the life of our ordinary lives, you know, at work, etc., seems to me then to give us a little bit of latitude as to this right livelihood.

76
00:07:42,627 --> 00:07:42,747
Right.

77
00:07:43,942 --> 00:07:48,927
I'm tending to think of it more as right lifestyle.

78
00:07:49,629 --> 00:07:57,598
So for instance, I Googled what were the important qualities of a police officer.

79
00:08:00,041 --> 00:08:12,817
And it's got physical fitness, critical thinking, problem solving skills, communication skills, interpersonal skills, strong moral character, devotion to the community.

80
00:08:13,574 --> 00:08:17,098
And then I looked up what was a successful nurse practitioner.

81
00:08:17,939 --> 00:08:19,980
So empathy comes at the top there.

82
00:08:20,500 --> 00:08:29,370
Enthusiasm, an intense and eager enjoyment accompanied by a big grin and a list of questions.

83
00:08:30,951 --> 00:08:33,916
Tenacity, creativity, integrity.

84
00:08:34,937 --> 00:08:42,804
And when I looked up, I put in common traits of a good employee, 54 million responses came.

85
00:08:43,038 --> 00:08:51,028
And there's a whole list, dedication, confidence, reliability, teamwork, independence.

86
00:08:52,169 --> 00:08:52,910
That's interesting.

87
00:08:52,971 --> 00:08:59,158
Teamwork and independence, leadership, interpersonal communication skills and self-awareness.

88
00:08:59,538 --> 00:09:02,363
Now, whatever job you're doing.

89
00:09:02,714 --> 00:09:07,820
And of course, if you're retired, you'll be doing something with your life.

90
00:09:08,640 --> 00:09:15,369
All these activities, of course, reinforce certain parts of our characters and personalities.

91
00:09:17,371 --> 00:09:30,847
And it might be worth just thinking about what you're doing and how it's affecting you personally, your characters, personalities, and then doing something which does the opposite.

92
00:09:31,216 --> 00:09:33,441
So that you get a sort of balance.

93
00:09:33,461 --> 00:09:37,729
So I remember, you know, at work, I was teaching.

94
00:09:37,749 --> 00:09:40,816
I really got fed up with all the head stuff.

95
00:09:40,836 --> 00:09:41,937
It's always head stuff.

96
00:09:41,957 --> 00:09:43,841
You're always talking about stuff.

97
00:09:44,631 --> 00:09:54,621
And I got to a point where this is when I was practicing that I really felt I needed if I was going to progress, I really needed to do something physical.

98
00:09:55,462 --> 00:09:58,767
So I got the idea in my head that I'd be a great cook.

99
00:09:58,787 --> 00:10:04,613
So I went for a week, a week's introduction to vegetarian cooking.

100
00:10:05,553 --> 00:10:10,639
By the end of the week, by the way, I knew I didn't want to be a cook, but it did give me confidence.

101
00:10:11,648 --> 00:10:14,030
There's too much vegetable shopping.

102
00:10:14,051 --> 00:10:22,142
But it did give me, you know, a sort of a physical base because I'm not I haven't been brought up to take care of gardens or anything like that.

103
00:10:23,403 --> 00:10:30,133
And so I just found ways of of bringing into my life something that was physical.

104
00:10:30,192 --> 00:10:33,337
And so I started doing things like Tai Chi and stuff.

105
00:10:34,639 --> 00:10:35,900
So.

106
00:10:36,184 --> 00:10:45,062
You can imagine that if somebody, say, runs a business, so their mind is always really caught up in running costs and profit.

107
00:10:45,543 --> 00:10:49,269
I mean, I know that just running this little centre, you're always worried about running costs.

108
00:10:49,870 --> 00:10:58,868
And it'd just be nice to balance that with doing some charitable work where those sorts of thoughts just don't come in.

109
00:11:00,602 --> 00:11:11,405
So it's a case of, I think, perhaps translating that right livelihood in a wider sense and just looking at our lives, trying to get that balance right.

110
00:11:13,546 --> 00:11:24,857
And that would include, of course, our leisure pursuits, you know, the films, the reading, walking, looking after the body, flying drones, things like that.

111
00:11:25,739 --> 00:11:35,470
So anything that we do, which is our pastime, and to sort of get a global view of our lives.

112
00:11:36,870 --> 00:11:42,236
And I think that, and then to sort of make it sense to the centre,

113
00:11:42,722 --> 00:11:48,469
I don't know whether they have them anymore, but in the old fairs, I'm sure they do, really.

114
00:11:48,889 --> 00:11:51,071
They used to have these roundabouts with different animals.

115
00:11:51,431 --> 00:11:55,254
You know, you could you could ride a horse or a bear or a pig.

116
00:11:55,836 --> 00:11:58,839
And if you go round and round with this silly music, you know, as a kid.

117
00:11:59,980 --> 00:12:09,428
And if our lives are unconnected, we tend to go from one thing to another, really just to keep busy, keep occupied and so on and so forth.

118
00:12:10,089 --> 00:12:11,750
But there's no sort of connection.

119
00:12:12,541 --> 00:12:26,635
But if you were sort of centered on the Dharma, on what you understand to be your personal spiritual path, then everything you do has to make sense to that particular position.

120
00:12:28,278 --> 00:12:39,509
One thing that happens to a lot of people when they start practicing, definitely happened to me, is that you find interests that you had begin to disappear.

121
00:12:39,625 --> 00:12:44,193
So I remember once, you know, listening to jazz.

122
00:12:44,214 --> 00:12:47,340
I used to go to jazz in pubs.

123
00:12:47,360 --> 00:12:50,506
And I remember this was a special night.

124
00:12:50,567 --> 00:12:52,851
They had this American trumpeter.

125
00:12:52,871 --> 00:12:56,097
I can't remember the name, but he was phenomenal.

126
00:12:56,077 --> 00:13:02,226
And the backing group were finding it really difficult to keep up with him.

127
00:13:02,267 --> 00:13:07,453
You know, you could see them sweating, trying to keep up with the speed of his playing.

128
00:13:08,215 --> 00:13:14,845
And just somehow, you know, halfway through the performance, I just got this feeling that, you know, I was wasting time.

129
00:13:15,085 --> 00:13:16,788
It just didn't make any sense to me anymore.

130
00:13:17,489 --> 00:13:23,857
And just after that particular performance, I sort of made my excuses and left.

131
00:13:24,461 --> 00:13:34,490
So you find that your life begins to collect around those things that make sense to the heart of your dharma.

132
00:13:36,316 --> 00:13:37,779
And, you know, it's like...

133
00:13:39,211 --> 00:13:43,437
If you don't, I mean, a lot of people, for instance, you know, don't know where they're going.

134
00:13:43,477 --> 00:13:49,748
So I like to quote Lewis Carroll, you know, if you don't know where you're going, any road will take you there.

135
00:13:50,929 --> 00:13:55,616
But the thing is, some wit also said, how do you know when you've arrived?

136
00:13:56,895 --> 00:14:09,825
So at least the Buddhist path is fairly clear for us, gives us parameters and allows us to be very creative within that too.

137
00:14:09,990 --> 00:14:17,001
Often when people think of the monastic life, they think it's sort of just one type of livelihood.

138
00:14:17,743 --> 00:14:22,370
Maybe they know the forest tradition and all you do is meditate all the time.

139
00:14:22,890 --> 00:14:30,462
But there's quite a variety of things that you can do and become involved in as a monastic.

140
00:14:31,674 --> 00:14:43,312
I'm thinking things like, you know, the study part, many become, you know, many take degrees and stuff like that.

141
00:14:43,633 --> 00:14:45,355
Other people involved in the community.

142
00:14:46,015 --> 00:14:52,164
I know in Colombo, for instance, there was a monk who was a constant visitor to the hospital, things like that.

143
00:14:52,481 --> 00:15:03,472
So there's a whole load of variety in life, but we have to think of it in terms of where I'm standing in the Dharma and how it makes sense to it.

144
00:15:04,413 --> 00:15:08,697
You might find, again, as I did, that certain friends drop away.

145
00:15:09,719 --> 00:15:12,400
It's not as though you end up telling them to go away.

146
00:15:12,861 --> 00:15:14,442
You just stop seeing them.

147
00:15:15,004 --> 00:15:18,126
It's just that a different social scene begins to appear.

148
00:15:19,948 --> 00:15:21,190
So...

149
00:15:22,519 --> 00:15:23,341
There we have it.

150
00:15:23,520 --> 00:15:42,384
I think we are closer to the idea of the spiritual life if we just extend that word, right livelihood, which is the direct translation, sama abidja, right livelihood, and just see it more, right livelihood.

151
00:15:42,365 --> 00:15:52,186
Right work, the work we have, if we just extend that to include everything we do, so it becomes like a right lifestyle.

152
00:15:52,986 --> 00:16:00,001
I think that would be a much more profitable way of looking at it.

153
00:16:01,804 --> 00:16:15,611
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, that they have not caused confusion and that by your devotion to right lifestyle, you will be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

